ðŸ’³ Customer Segmentation for Credit Card Portfolio Optimization
This project applies Unsupervised Machine Learning (K-Means Clustering) to segment credit card customers. The resulting profiles enable financial institutions to move beyond simple demographics, allowing for tailored product offerings, optimized marketing expenditure, and enhanced financial risk management strategies.

ðŸŽ¯ Strategic Business Value
Targeted Marketing: Identified distinct customer segments to design personalized campaigns, maximizing return on investment (ROI) in marketing spend.

Risk Profile Prediction: Provided data to inform risk models by identifying clusters associated with specific income and credit limit tiers.

Product Personalization: Enabled product teams to tailor credit card features (e.g., rewards, interest rates) to specific high-value or high-risk segments.
Methodology and key findings:
Data Cleaning	Pandas, NumPy	Handled missing values and mapped complex categorical data (Gender, Income Category) to numerical values to prepare the dataset for modeling.
Feature Scaling	MinMaxScaler	Normalized key features (Credit Limit) to prevent variables with larger ranges from dominating the clustering process.
Clustering Model	K-Means Clustering	Successfully segmented the customer base into five distinct clusters based on their financial attributes (Gender, Income, Credit Limit).
Visualization	Matplotlib, Plotly (3D Scatter Plot)	Created a 3D visualization to clearly illustrate the separation of customer clusters, providing an intuitive understanding of segment profiles for non-technical stakeholders.

ðŸ“ˆ Conclusion and Recommendation
The analysis successfully identified five distinct customer segments, revealing critical patterns such as a High-Income/High-Limit Segment (ideal for premium card upsells) and a Low-Income/Mid-Limit Segment (requiring careful risk monitoring).

Recommendation: Deploy the segment labels in the institution's CRM system to power tailored digital offers and implement segment-specific credit policies to optimize portfolio profitability and mitigate unexpected risk.

ðŸ›  Tools and Techniques Used
Programming Language: Python

Libraries: Pandas, NumPy (Data Manipulation), Scikit-learn (K-Means Clustering, MinMaxScaler), Matplotlib, Plotly (Advanced Visualization).

Techniques: Unsupervised Learning, Feature Engineering, Dimensionality Reduction (Implicit).
